I tried out GitHub's Copilot agent mode, and it seems to mostly be a wrapper around GitHub Actions, some opaque CLI, and some MCP servers.

As such it shouldn't surprise anyone to learn that it doesn't pin its actions dependencies, and has surprising permissions granted to it. Be careful out there!

One thing I had not anticipated in the fight against realistic AI video fakes, was that folks would also start using AI upscaling and compression, which would make legitimate videos harder for folks to distinguish from fakes.

Seems like a bit of an own-goal IMO.

1. AI is a double-edged sword—but not inherently malicious.
While it's true that AI can be used to enhance cyberattacks, it’s equally (if not more) powerful in defending against them. AI-driven cybersecurity tools are already being used to:

Detect anomalies in network traffic in real time.
Automate threat hunting and incident response.
Predict and prevent phishing attacks using behavioral analysis.
The narrative that AI is primarily a threat overlooks the massive investments and innovations in AI-powered defense systems.

Governments, enterprises, and standards bodies are actively working on AI governance frameworks, including:

NIST’s AI Risk Management Framework
EU AI Act
U.S. Executive Orders on AI Safety and Security
These efforts aim to ensure that AI systems are secure, transparent, and resilient against misuse—including in cybersecurity contexts.

This idea likely refers to adversarial attacks or prompt injection vulnerabilities in LLMs. While these are real concerns, they are being actively researched and mitigated. Most enterprise-grade AI systems now include:

Input sanitization
Guardrails and red-teaming
Continuous model monitoring

AI doesn’t introduce new types of attacks—it scales existing ones. For example:

Phishing emails can be more convincing.
Malware can adapt faster.
Reconnaissance can be automated.
But these are evolutions, not revolutions. The cybersecurity industry has always adapted to technological shifts—from cloud to mobile to IoT—and AI is no different.

Great question. That take has some fair points (like Nvidia’s desire to broaden its customer base and the reality of “cognitive greed” for better models), but it also contains flaws or blind spots when you examine the economics and incentives more closely. Here are some angles to debate:

1. Overstating “insatiable demand”

It’s true that people always want better models, but demand in practice is constrained by costs, latency, and ROI.

Enterprises often don’t need cutting-edge GPT-4-class performance for most workloads—GPT-3.5 is already “good enough” for summarization, classification, or customer support.

The idea that demand will infinitely scale just because “we’re cognitively greedy” ignores budgetary constraints and the reality that businesses optimize for cost/performance, not novelty.

2. Circular capital recycling doesn’t guarantee durable markets

Nvidia putting $100B into startups that then turn around and buy Nvidia GPUs can look like self-referential demand engineering, not organic demand growth.

It’s similar to the dot-com bubble where telcos financed startups that became their biggest bandwidth customers—until demand collapsed.

The flaw is treating recycled capital flows as proof of sustainable long-term demand rather than a short-term demand stimulus.

3. Underestimating the hyperscaler threat

The argument correctly notes that Amazon, Google, and Microsoft are designing custom silicon, but it waves away the real strategic risk: if hyperscalers succeed, Nvidia’s margins erode.

Supporting new ecosystem players doesn’t automatically offset losing their biggest, deepest-pocketed customers. Most startups can’t match hyperscalers’ capex, and many will fail before reaching scale.

The take assumes monetization will catch up eventually because the models are “valuable to society.”
